    ("Physics", "Current Electricity", "The number density of free electrons in copper is 8.5 x 10^28 m^-3. How long does an electron take to drift from one end of a 3.0 m wire to the other? (Area = 2.0 x 10^-6 m^2, current = 3.0 A).", "v_d = I / (nAe). Time t = l / v_d = (l * n * A * e) / I = 2.7 x 10^4 seconds.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Current Electricity", "Calculate the steady state current through a 2 ohm resistor in a circuit containing a capacitor in parallel.", "In DC steady state, the capacitor acts as an open circuit (blocks DC). Calculate the equivalent resistance of the remaining closed loops to find the current.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Current Electricity", "A nichrome heating element (230 V supply) draws an initial current of 3.2 A which settles to 2.8 A. What is the steady temperature? (Room temp 27 C, alpha = 1.7 x 10^-4 /C)", "R1 = 230/3.2 = 71.87 ohms, R2 = 230/2.8 = 82.14 ohms. Using R2 = R1(1 + alpha*dT), steady temperature is 867 C.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Current Electricity", "Explain how the resistance of a semiconductor changes with an increase in temperature.", "It decreases exponentially. Increased thermal energy breaks covalent bonds, exponentially increasing the number of charge carriers (n) in the conduction band.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Current Electricity", "Two wires of equal length, one of copper and the other of manganin, have the same resistance. Which wire is thicker?", "The manganin wire is thicker because its resistivity (rho) is much higher than copper, requiring a larger area (A) to maintain the same resistance.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Current Electricity", "Derive the expression for maximum power dissipated in an external resistor connected to a cell.", "Power P = I^2 R = (E / (R+r))^2 * R. By differentiating dP/dR and setting to zero, P is max when R = r. P_max = E^2 / 4r.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Current Electricity", "V-I graph for a metallic wire at two temperatures T1 and T2 is shown. If the T1 curve is steeper (closer to V-axis), which temperature is higher?", "T1 is higher. A steeper slope on a V (y-axis) vs I (x-axis) graph means higher resistance, and metal resistance increases with temperature.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Current Electricity", "Six lead-acid secondary cells (emf 2.0 V, internal resistance 0.015 ohm each) are joined in series to a resistance of 8.5 ohms. What is the current drawn?", "Total E = 12.0 V. Total r = 0.09 ohm. I = E_total / (R + r_total) = 12 / (8.5 + 0.09) = 1.4 A.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Current Electricity", "Estimate the average drift speed of conduction electrons in a copper wire of area 1.0 x 10^-7 m^2 carrying 1.5 A. (Assume n = 9 x 10^28 m^-3).", "v_d = I / (nAe) = 1.5 / (9 x 10^28 * 1.0 x 10^-7 * 1.6 x 10^-19) = 1.04 x 10^-3 m/s.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Current Electricity", "Explain the variation of resistivity with temperature for a semiconductor using rho = m / (n e^2 tau).", "As temperature increases, the exponential increase in the number density of charge carriers (n) completely overpowers the slight decrease in relaxation time (tau), causing resistivity (rho) to decrease.", "HARD"),
    # Moving Charges and Magnetism
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "What is the SI unit of magnetic field?", "Tesla (T)", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Write the formula for Lorentz force.", "F = q(E + v × B)", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "What is the magnetic force on a current-carrying wire of length L?", "F = I(L × B)", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Which rule gives the direction of the magnetic field around a straight current-carrying wire?", "Right Hand Thumb Rule", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "What is the value of the permeability of free space (μ0)?", "4π x 10^-7 T m A^-1", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Write the formula for the radius of the circular path of a charge in a perpendicular magnetic field.", "r = mv/qB", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "What is the magnetic field at the center of a circular loop carrying current I?", "B = μ0I/2R", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "State the mathematical form of Ampere's Circuital Law.", "∮ B·dl = μ0I", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "What is the magnetic field due to an infinitely long straight wire carrying current I?", "B = μ0I/2πr", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Write the expression for force per unit length between two parallel current-carrying wires.", "f = (μ0 I1 I2) / (2π d)", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "What is the magnetic field inside an ideal, long solenoid?", "B = μ0nI", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Write the expression for torque on a current loop in a uniform magnetic field.", "τ = m × B", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "How do you convert a galvanometer into an ammeter?", "By connecting a low resistance (shunt) in parallel", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "How do you convert a galvanometer into a voltmeter?", "By connecting a high resistance in series", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "What is the magnetic field at the center of a circular current loop of radius R carrying current I?", "B = (mu_0 * I) / (2 * R)", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Write the formula for the magnetic force on a moving charge.", "F = q(v x B)", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Under what condition does a moving charge in a magnetic field experience maximum force?", "When its velocity vector is exactly perpendicular to the magnetic field vector (theta = 90 degrees).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "What is the work done by a magnetic field on a moving charge?", "Zero, because the magnetic force is always perpendicular to the direction of motion (velocity).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Define 1 Ampere using the force between two parallel current-carrying conductors.", "1 Ampere is the current which, flowing through two infinitely long parallel wires 1 m apart in a vacuum, produces a force of 2 x 10^-7 N per meter.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "What is the purpose of a radial magnetic field in a moving coil galvanometer?", "To ensure that the plane of the coil is always parallel to the magnetic field, making the torque maximum and uniform (theta = 90).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "How is the current sensitivity of a galvanometer defined?", "The deflection produced per unit current (I_s = phi / I = NAB / k).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Write the expression for the magnetic field inside a toroid.", "B = mu_0 * n * I, where n is the number of turns per unit length.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "State the Right-Hand Grip Rule for a straight wire.", "If you grasp the wire with your right hand such that the thumb points in the direction of current, the curled fingers indicate the direction of the magnetic field lines.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Does a stationary charge produce a magnetic field?", "No, only moving charges (currents) produce magnetic fields.", "MODERATE"),
    # Moving Charges and Magnetism - HIGH
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Derive the expression for the magnetic field at a point on the axis of a circular current-carrying loop.", "B = (mu_0 * I * R^2) / [2 * (R^2 + x^2)^(3/2)] directed along the axis.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Using Ampere's circuital law, derive the magnetic field due to a long straight current-carrying wire.", "Integral of B.dl = mu_0 * I. Since B and dl are parallel, B * 2*pi*r = mu_0 * I, yielding B = (mu_0 * I) / (2*pi*r).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Deduce the expression for the force per unit length between two infinitely long straight parallel wires carrying currents I1 and I2.", "f = (mu_0 * I1 * I2) / (2 * pi * d). They attract if currents are parallel, repel if anti-parallel.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Explain the principle and working of a moving coil galvanometer.", "A current-carrying coil in a uniform magnetic field experiences a deflecting torque (NABI) which is balanced by the restoring torque of the suspension spring (k*phi).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "How can a galvanometer of resistance G and full-scale current I_g be converted into an ammeter of range 0-I?", "By connecting a very low resistance (shunt) in parallel. S = (I_g * G) / (I - I_g).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "How can a galvanometer of resistance G be converted into a voltmeter of range 0-V?", "By connecting a very high resistance R in series. R = (V / I_g) - G.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Derive an expression for the torque experienced by a rectangular current loop placed in a uniform magnetic field.", "Forces on parallel sides cancel out translationally but create a couple. Torque tau = N * I * A * B * sin(theta).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "An electron moves in a circular orbit of radius r with uniform speed v. Derive an expression for its magnetic moment.", "Current I = e/T = ev/(2*pi*r). Area A = pi*r^2. Magnetic moment m = I*A = (e*v*r)/2.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "A square coil of side 10 cm has 20 turns and carries 12 A. The normal to the plane makes 30 degrees with a 0.80 T field. What is the torque?", "tau = N I A B sin(theta) = 20 * 12 * (0.01) * 0.80 * sin(30) = 0.96 N m.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Use Biot-Savart law to derive the magnetic field at the center of a circular coil of N turns.", "dB = (mu_0 * I * dl * sin(90)) / (4*pi*R^2). Integrating over the full circle (L = 2*pi*R*N) gives B = (mu_0 * N * I) / (2 * R).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "A straight wire carrying 12 A is bent into a semi-circular arc of radius 2.0 cm. What is the magnetic field at the center of the arc?", "B = 1/2 * (mu_0 * I / 2R) = 1.9 x 10^-4 T.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Two identical concentric coils of radius R carry currents 1 A and sqrt(3) A in perpendicular planes (XY and YZ). Find the net magnetic field at the center.", "B1 = mu_0(1)/2R, B2 = mu_0(sqrt(3))/2R. Net B = sqrt(B1^2 + B2^2) = (mu_0/2R) * sqrt(1+3) = mu_0 / R.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Explain why the magnetic field inside a tightly wound long solenoid is uniform and parallel to its axis.", "The magnetic fields generated by adjacent circular turns add up along the central axis and cancel each other out in the perpendicular direction.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "An alpha particle and a proton enter a uniform magnetic field with the same velocity perpendicularly. Find the ratio of the radii of their paths.", "r = mv/qB. r_alpha / r_p = (m_alpha/q_alpha) / (m_p/q_p) = (4m / 2e) / (m / e) = 2:1.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "An alpha particle and a proton enter a uniform magnetic field with the same kinetic energy. Find the ratio of their radii.", "r = sqrt(2mK)/qB. r_alpha / r_p = sqrt(m_alpha)/q_alpha / sqrt(m_p)/q_p = sqrt(4)/2 / sqrt(1)/1 = 1:1.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Explain the concept of a velocity selector.", "Using crossed (perpendicular) electric and magnetic fields, only charged particles moving with a specific velocity v = E/B pass through undeflected.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "A long wire carries 4 A. A proton travels at 4 x 10^6 m/s parallel to the wire, 0.2 m from it, opposite to the current. Calculate the force on the proton.", "B = mu_0*I/(2*pi*r) = 4 x 10^-6 T. F = qvB = (1.6 x 10^-19)*(4 x 10^6)*(4 x 10^-6) = 2.56 x 10^-19 N (Repulsive).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "What is the gyromagnetic ratio of an electron? State its value.", "It is the ratio of its magnetic dipole moment to its orbital angular momentum (e/2m). Its value is constant at 8.8 x 10^10 C/kg.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "Why do we prefer phosphor-bronze alloy for the suspension wire in a moving coil galvanometer?", "Because it has a very low restoring torque per unit twist (k) and high tensile strength.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "State Ampere's circuital law. How does its application differ from the Biot-Savart law?", "The line integral of B over a closed loop equals mu_0 * I_enclosed. It is highly useful for highly symmetric current configurations, whereas Biot-Savart is universal.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Moving Charges and Magnetism", "A steady current flows in a network consisting of two concentric circular loops of radii R and 2R. If they carry the same current I in opposite directions, find the net magnetic field at the center.", "B_net = (mu_0 * I / 2R) - (mu_0 * I / 4R) = mu_0 * I / 4R.", "HARD"),
    # Magnetism and Matter
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "What is the SI unit of magnetic dipole moment?", "A m^2", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "What is the angle of dip at the Earth's magnetic equator?", "Zero degrees", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "What is the angle of dip at the Earth's magnetic poles?", "90 degrees", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "Are diamagnetic materials attracted or repelled by a magnet?", "Feebly repelled", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "Are ferromagnetic materials attracted or repelled by a magnet?", "Strongly attracted", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "What happens to a ferromagnetic material above the Curie temperature?", "It becomes paramagnetic", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "What is the relationship between relative permeability (μr) and magnetic susceptibility (χ)?", "μr = 1 + χ", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "What does the area enclosed by a hysteresis loop represent?", "Energy dissipated as heat per cycle of magnetization", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "Define retentivity.", "The magnetic flux density remaining when the magnetizing field is reduced to zero", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "Define coercivity.", "The reverse magnetizing field required to completely demagnetize a material", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "Define magnetic susceptibility.", "It is the ratio of the intensity of magnetization (M) induced in a material to the magnetizing field intensity (H).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "What are paramagnetic materials?", "Materials that develop a weak induced magnetization in the direction of the applied magnetic field (weakly attracted).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "What are diamagnetic materials?", "Materials that develop a weak induced magnetization in the opposite direction to the applied magnetic field (weakly repelled).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "What is the SI unit of magnetic pole strength?", "Ampere-meter (A m).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "Define Bohr magneton.", "The minimum magnetic dipole moment associated with an electron revolving in the first orbit of a Hydrogen atom.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "How does the magnetic susceptibility of a diamagnetic substance depend on temperature?", "It is almost completely independent of temperature.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "State Curie's law for paramagnetic substances.", "The magnetic susceptibility of a paramagnetic material is inversely proportional to its absolute temperature (chi = C/T).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "What is the value of the angle of dip at the Earth's magnetic equator?", "Zero degrees.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "What happens when a diamagnetic substance is placed in a non-uniform magnetic field?", "It tends to move slowly from the stronger part of the magnetic field to the weaker part.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "Name the magnetic material used for making permanent magnets and why.", "Steel or Alnico, because they possess high retentivity and exceptionally high coercivity.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "Derive the expression for the time period of oscillation of a magnetic dipole in a uniform magnetic field.", "Restoring torque tau = -mB sin(theta) = I * alpha. For small angles, I * (d^2 theta / dt^2) = -mB * theta. Solving gives T = 2 * pi * sqrt(I / mB).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "Explain the hysteresis loop for a ferromagnetic material.", "It is the phenomenon where the magnetic flux density (B) lags behind the magnetizing field (H) when the material is subjected to a cycle of magnetization.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "Compare the properties of dia, para, and ferromagnetic materials in terms of susceptibility (chi) and relative permeability (mu_r).", "Dia: chi < 0, mu_r < 1. Para: chi > 0 (small), mu_r > 1. Ferro: chi >> 0 (large), mu_r >> 1.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "A short bar magnet placed with its axis at 30 degrees to a uniform field of 0.25 T experiences a torque of 4.5 x 10^-2 J. What is its magnetic moment?", "tau = mB sin(theta). 0.045 = m * 0.25 * 0.5. m = 0.36 J/T.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "A short bar magnet (m = 0.32 J/T) is in a field of 0.15 T. What orientations correspond to its stable and unstable equilibrium?", "Stable equilibrium occurs when aligned parallel to the field (theta = 0). Unstable occurs when anti-parallel (theta = 180).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "What is the potential energy of the magnet in stable and unstable equilibrium in the previous question?", "U = -mB cos(theta). Stable: U = - (0.32)(0.15) = -0.048 J. Unstable: U = +0.048 J.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "Explain the origin of diamagnetism on the basis of atomic structure.", "It arises due to the orbital motion of electrons. According to Lenz's law, an external magnetic field induces a net magnetic moment that opposes the applied field.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "A closely wound solenoid of 800 turns and area 2.5 x 10^-4 m^2 carries 3.0 A. What is its associated magnetic moment?", "m = N I A = 800 * 3.0 * (2.5 x 10^-4) = 0.6 J/T directed along the axis of the solenoid.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "State Gauss's law in magnetism. What fundamental fact does it signify?", "The net magnetic flux through any closed surface is zero. It signifies that magnetic monopoles do not exist; magnetic poles always exist in pairs.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "Define magnetization vector (M). Write its SI unit.", "It is defined as the net magnetic dipole moment developed per unit volume of the material. SI unit is Ampere/meter (A/m).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "How does the intensity of magnetization of a paramagnetic material vary with increasing applied magnetic field and temperature?", "It increases directly with the applied magnetic field and decreases inversely with absolute temperature (until saturation).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "Differentiate between soft iron and steel on the basis of their hysteresis curves.", "Soft iron has a narrow hysteresis loop, low coercivity, and high retentivity. Steel has a wider loop and much higher coercivity.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "Why are electromagnets made of soft iron?", "Because soft iron has high initial permeability (easily magnetized) and low retentivity (quickly demagnetized when current stops).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "The horizontal component of the earth's magnetic field is B and angle of dip is 60 degrees. What is the vertical component?", "tan(delta) = V / H. tan(60) = V / B. Vertical component V = B * sqrt(3).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "A compass needle in the center of a vertical coil (30 turns, radius 12 cm, 45 deg to magnetic meridian, 0.35 A current) points West-East. Find Earth's horizontal field.", "The coil's field B_c must exactly cancel Earth's horizontal field H. B_c = mu_0*N*I/(2R) = 5.5 x 10^-5 T. H = B_c * sin(45) = 3.9 x 10^-5 T.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "Explain the Meissner effect in superconductors.", "Superconductors exhibit perfect diamagnetism (chi = -1); they completely expel magnetic field lines from their interior when cooled below their critical temperature.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "Find the magnetic field due to a magnetic dipole of dipole moment M at a distance r on its equatorial line.", "B = (mu_0 / 4*pi) * (M / r^3), directed anti-parallel to the magnetic dipole moment.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "What is the work done in rotating a magnet of magnetic moment M in a uniform magnetic field B from 0 to 90 degrees?", "W = -MB(cos(90) - cos(0)) = -MB(0 - 1) = +MB.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "Why is diamagnetism considered a universal property of all materials?", "Because all materials are made of atoms containing revolving electrons, which inherently produce opposing induced magnetic moments in a magnetic field.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Magnetism and Matter", "An electron moves around the nucleus in a circular orbit of radius r. Deduce the expression for the magnetic field produced at the center of the orbit.", "Current I = e*v / (2*pi*r). B = mu_0*I / (2r) = (mu_0 * e * v) / (4 * pi * r^2).", "HARD"),
    # Electromagnetic Induction
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "State Faraday's Law of Electromagnetic Induction?.", "The induced emf is equal to the negative rate of change of magnetic flux (e = -dΦ/dt)", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Lenz's Law is a consequence of which conservation law?", "Conservation of Energy", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "What is the SI unit of magnetic flux?", "Weber (Wb)", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "What is the SI unit of self-inductance and mutual inductance?", "Henry (H)", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Write the formula for motional emf.", "e = Blv", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "What is the self-inductance of a long air-cored solenoid?", "L = μ0 n^2 A l", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Write the formula for the energy stored in an inductor.", "U = 1/2 LI^2", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "What are eddy currents?", "Currents induced in the body of a bulk piece of conductor subjected to changing magnetic flux", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Name one practical application of eddy currents.", "Magnetic braking in trains (or induction furnaces)", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "An AC generator works on which fundamental principle?", "Electromagnetic Induction", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Define magnetic flux and state its SI unit.", "Magnetic flux is the total number of magnetic field lines passing normally through a given area. Its SI unit is Weber (Wb).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "State Faraday's law of electromagnetic induction.", "The magnitude of the induced emf in a circuit is equal to the time rate of change of magnetic flux through the circuit.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "State Lenz's law.", "The direction of the induced current is such that it opposes the change in magnetic flux that produces it.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "What is the formula for motional emf in a straight conductor moving perpendicular to a magnetic field?", "e = Bvl (where B is magnetic field, v is velocity, l is length).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Define self-inductance.", "It is the property of a coil by virtue of which it opposes any change in the strength of current flowing through it by inducing an emf in itself.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Define mutual inductance.", "It is the property of two coils by virtue of which each opposes any change in the strength of current flowing through the other by developing an induced emf.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "What are eddy currents?", "Circulating currents induced in a bulk piece of metal when it is subjected to a changing magnetic flux.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Write the formula for the energy stored in an inductor.", "U = 1/2 * L * I^2", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "What is the dimensional formula of magnetic flux?", "[M L^2 T^-2 A^-1]", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "State Fleming's Right-Hand Rule.", "Stretch thumb, forefinger, and middle finger of the right hand mutually perpendicular. If forefinger points to magnetic field and thumb to motion, middle finger points to induced current.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "How does Lenz's law justify the principle of conservation of energy?", "The mechanical work done in moving a magnet against the repulsive/attractive force of the induced current is transformed into electrical energy.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Derive the expression for motional emf (e = Bvl) using the concept of Lorentz force.", "A charge q in the rod experiences magnetic force F_m = qvB. This moves charges until electric field E is set up where qE = qvB, so E = vB. Emf e = El = Bvl.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Derive the expression for power dissipated in moving a conductor of length l with velocity v in a transverse magnetic field B.", "Induced emf e = Bvl. Current I = Bvl/R. Force required F = BIl = B^2 l^2 v / R. Power P = Fv = (B^2 l^2 v^2) / R.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Derive the expression for the self-inductance of a long air-cored solenoid.", "Flux linkage N(phi) = (nl) * (mu_0 n I) * A = mu_0 n^2 A l I. Since N(phi) = LI, L = mu_0 n^2 A l.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Derive the expression for the mutual inductance of two long coaxial solenoids.", "M = mu_0 * n1 * n2 * pi * r1^2 * l, where r1 is the radius of the inner solenoid.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Explain the principle and working of an AC generator.", "It works on the principle of electromagnetic induction. A coil is rotated in a uniform magnetic field, continuously changing the flux and inducing an alternating emf.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Derive the expression for the instantaneous emf induced in an AC generator.", "Flux phi = NBA cos(wt). Induced emf e = -d(phi)/dt = NBAw sin(wt), where e_0 = NBAw is the peak emf.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "How does the self-inductance of a coil change when an iron core is inserted into it?", "It increases significantly because the permeability of iron (mu) is much greater than that of free space (mu_0).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "A metallic wheel with 10 spokes, each 0.5 m long, is rotated with an angular velocity of 120 rev/min in a magnetic field of 0.4 G. What is the induced emf?", "e = 1/2 * B * w * R^2 = 1/2 * (0.4 x 10^-4) * (4 * pi) * (0.5)^2 = 6.28 x 10^-5 V.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Two circular coils are placed near each other. If the distance between them is increased, what happens to their mutual inductance?", "The mutual inductance decreases because the magnetic flux linked with the secondary coil due to the primary coil decreases.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "State two ways to minimize eddy currents in the core of a transformer.", "By using a laminated core (thin sheets insulated from each other) and by using magnetic materials with high electrical resistivity.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Write two practical applications of eddy currents.", "Electromagnetic braking in trains and induction furnaces for melting metals.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Deduce the expression for the total charge induced in a circuit due to a change in magnetic flux.", "I = dq/dt = e/R = (-d(phi)/dt) / R. Integrating gives q = (Delta phi) / R. (Charge is independent of time taken).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "A jet plane is travelling towards the west at 1800 km/h. What is the voltage difference developed between the ends of the wing having a span of 25 m? (Earth's magnetic field = 5 x 10^-4 T, dip = 30 deg).", "Vertical component B_v = B sin(30) = 2.5 x 10^-4 T. Velocity v = 500 m/s. Emf = B_v * v * l = (2.5 x 10^-4) * 500 * 25 = 3.125 V.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "What is back emf in a DC motor? Why is it called so?", "When the armature rotates in the magnetic field, an emf is induced which opposes the applied voltage according to Lenz's law. Hence it is called back emf.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Current in a circuit falls from 5.0 A to 0.0 A in 0.1 s. If an average emf of 200 V is induced, calculate the self-inductance of the circuit.", "e = L * (di/dt) -> 200 = L * (5 / 0.1) -> L = 4 H.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "A rectangular loop is pulled out of a uniform magnetic field at a constant velocity. Plot the variation of induced emf with time.", "The emf is constant (e = Bvl) as long as the trailing edge is inside the field, and drops abruptly to zero the moment it exits.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Show that the mutual inductance of coil 1 with respect to coil 2 (M12) is equal to that of coil 2 with respect to coil 1 (M21).", "Using the reciprocity theorem of mutual inductance, the flux linked per unit current is geometrically symmetric for both coils, hence M12 = M21 = M.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "An inductor of 2 H carries a current of 5 A. How much energy is stored in the magnetic field?", "U = 1/2 * L * I^2 = 1/2 * 2 * 25 = 25 Joules.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Induction", "Why does a metallic pendulum damp much faster when it swings in a uniform magnetic field?", "Because eddy currents are induced in the metallic bob, which dissipate the mechanical energy of the pendulum as heat (Joule heating) according to Lenz's law.", "HARD"),
    # Alternating Current
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "What is the relation between peak current (I0) and RMS current (Irms)?", "Irms = I0 / √2", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "What is the frequency of AC supply in India?", "50 Hz", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Write the formula for the power factor in an AC circuit.", "cos Φ = R/Z", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "What is the formula for inductive reactance (XL)?", "XL = ωL", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "What is the formula for capacitive reactance (XC)?", "XC = 1/ωC", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Write the formula for the impedance (Z) of a series LCR circuit.", "Z = √(R^2 + (XL - XC)^2)", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "What is the condition for resonance in a series LCR circuit?", "XL = XC (or ωL = 1/ωC)", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Write the formula for the resonant frequency of an LCR circuit.", "f = 1 / (2π√LC)", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "On what principle does a transformer work?", "Mutual Induction", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "What is the turns ratio relation for an ideal transformer?", "Vs / Vp = Ns / Np", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "What is the relationship between the peak value (I_0) and RMS value (I_rms) of alternating current?", "I_rms = I_0 / sqrt(2)", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Write the formula for inductive reactance (X_L) and state its unit.", "X_L = wL = 2 * pi * f * L. Unit is Ohm.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Write the formula for capacitive reactance (X_C) and state its unit.", "X_C = 1 / (wC) = 1 / (2 * pi * f * C). Unit is Ohm.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "What is the phase difference between voltage and current in a purely resistive AC circuit?", "Zero (they are in the same phase).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "What is the phase difference between voltage and current in a purely inductive AC circuit?", "Voltage leads current by pi/2 (90 degrees).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Write the expression for the impedance (Z) of a series LCR circuit.", "Z = sqrt(R^2 + (X_L - X_C)^2)", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "State the condition for electrical resonance in a series LCR circuit.", "Inductive reactance equals capacitive reactance (X_L = X_C).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Write the formula for the resonant frequency of an LCR circuit.", "f_r = 1 / (2 * pi * sqrt(LC))", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Define power factor of an AC circuit.", "It is the cosine of the phase angle between voltage and current (cos(phi) = R/Z).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "What is the working principle of a transformer?", "Mutual induction (a changing current in the primary coil induces an emf in the secondary coil).", "MODERATE"),
    # Alternating Current - HIGH
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Derive the expression for the mean value of AC over a half cycle.", "Integrating I = I_0 sin(wt) from 0 to T/2 and dividing by T/2 yields I_mean = (2 * I_0) / pi = 0.637 I_0.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Show mathematically that the average power dissipated in a purely inductive circuit over a complete cycle is zero.", "P_avg = V_rms * I_rms * cos(90). Since cos(90) = 0, P_avg = 0. Energy oscillates between source and inductor.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Show mathematically that current leads voltage by pi/2 in a purely capacitive AC circuit.", "V = V_0 sin(wt). Q = CV. I = dQ/dt = d(C V_0 sin(wt))/dt = C V_0 w cos(wt) = I_0 sin(wt + pi/2).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Derive the expression for the impedance of a series LCR circuit using a phasor diagram.", "V_R is along I. V_L leads I by 90. V_C lags I by 90. Net reactive voltage is V_L - V_C. V_net^2 = V_R^2 + (V_L - V_C)^2. Substituting V=IZ yields Z = sqrt(R^2 + (X_L - X_C)^2).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Derive the expression for average power in a series LCR circuit.", "Instantaneous power P = VI = V_0 sin(wt) * I_0 sin(wt - phi). Integrating over a full cycle gives P_avg = (V_0 I_0 / 2) cos(phi) = V_rms I_rms cos(phi).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "What is wattless current?", "The component of the AC current (I_rms sin(phi)) which is perpendicular to the voltage and contributes zero average power dissipation.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Define Quality factor (Q-factor) of a resonant LCR circuit and write its formula.", "It is the ratio of resonant frequency to the bandwidth (sharpness of resonance). Q = (1/R) * sqrt(L/C).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Why are LC oscillations not realistic for an infinite time in a practical circuit?", "Because every inductor has some inherent resistance, which causes the energy to dissipate as heat (Joule heating), damping the oscillations.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Derive the turns ratio relationship for an ideal transformer.", "e_p = -N_p d(phi)/dt and e_s = -N_s d(phi)/dt. Dividing gives e_s / e_p = N_s / N_p. For ideal, V_s/V_p = N_s/N_p.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "List four main sources of energy loss in a transformer and how they are minimized.", "1. Copper loss (use thick wire). 2. Eddy currents (use laminated core). 3. Hysteresis loss (use soft iron core). 4. Flux leakage (wind primary and secondary over each other).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "In a step-up transformer, voltage increases. Does this violate the conservation of energy? Explain.", "No. As voltage increases, the current decreases proportionally in the secondary coil, ensuring input power equals output power (V_p I_p = V_s I_s).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Why is electrical power transmitted at high voltages over long distances?", "High voltage transmission means low current for the same power. This minimizes the I^2 R power losses in the transmission cables.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Explain the mechanical analogy of LC oscillations.", "It is analogous to a spring-mass block system. Inductance (L) represents mass (inertia), 1/Capacitance (1/C) represents the spring constant (k), and charge (q) represents displacement (x).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Plot graphs showing the variation of X_L and X_C with frequency of the AC source.", "X_L vs frequency is a straight line passing through the origin. X_C vs frequency is a rectangular hyperbola (inversely proportional).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "A series LCR circuit with R = 20 ohm, L = 1.5 H and C = 35 uF is connected to a variable-frequency 200V ac supply. What is the average power transferred to the circuit at resonance?", "At resonance, Z = R = 20 ohm. I_rms = 200/20 = 10 A. P_avg = I_rms^2 * R = 100 * 20 = 2000 W.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "What is the value of the power factor at resonance in an LCR circuit?", "At resonance, X_L = X_C, so Z = R. The phase angle phi = 0, so the power factor cos(phi) = 1 (maximum power).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Why is a choke coil preferred over a resistor to reduce current in an AC circuit?", "A choke coil reduces current by providing high inductive reactance while consuming almost zero average power (since cos(phi) is nearly 0), whereas a resistor wastes power as heat.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "Explain why a capacitor blocks DC but allows AC to pass through it.", "For DC, frequency f = 0, so X_C = 1/(2*pi*f*C) = infinity (infinite resistance). For AC, f > 0, so X_C is finite, allowing current to pass.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "In a series LCR circuit, the voltage across the inductor and capacitor are equal. What is the power factor of the circuit?", "If V_L = V_C, then X_L = X_C (resonance). The circuit is purely resistive, so the phase angle is 0 and the power factor is 1.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Alternating Current", "A bulb is connected in series with a capacitor to an AC source. What happens to the brightness of the bulb if the capacitance is increased?", "If C increases, X_C decreases. Total impedance Z decreases, leading to an increase in current. Hence, the brightness of the bulb increases.", "HARD"),
    # Electromagnetic Waves
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "What is the speed of electromagnetic waves in a vacuum?", "c = 3 x 10^8 m/s (or c = 1/√(μ0ε0))", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Which EM wave has the highest frequency?", "Gamma rays", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Which EM wave has the longest wavelength?", "Radio waves", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "What does the transverse nature of EM waves imply?", "Electric and magnetic fields are perpendicular to each other and to the direction of propagation", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "What is the source of electromagnetic waves?", "Accelerating (or oscillating) electric charges", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "What is the relationship between the amplitudes of the electric and magnetic fields in vacuum?", "E0 / B0 = c", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Write the formula for displacement current.", "Id = ε0 (dΦE/dt)", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Name the EM wave used in radar systems.", "Microwaves", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Name the EM wave used for water purification and killing bacteria.", "Ultraviolet (UV) rays", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "What represents the momentum p transferred by an EM wave of total energy U?", "p = U/c", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "What is the source of an electromagnetic wave?", "An accelerating or oscillating electric charge.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "What do you mean by the transverse nature of electromagnetic waves?", "The electric and magnetic field vectors are perpendicular to each other as well as to the direction of propagation of the wave.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Write the relation between the speed of light (c), permeability of free space (mu_0), and permittivity of free space (eps_0).", "c = 1 / sqrt(mu_0 _ eps_0)", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "What is the relationship between the amplitudes of the electric field (E0) and magnetic field (B0) in a vacuum?", "E0 / B0 = c (speed of light).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Define displacement current.", "It is the current that comes into existence in a region where the electric field (and hence the electric flux) is changing with time.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Which part of the electromagnetic spectrum is used in radar systems?", "Microwaves.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Which part of the electromagnetic spectrum is absorbed by the ozone layer?", "Ultraviolet (UV) rays.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Which electromagnetic waves have the highest frequency and shortest wavelength?", "Gamma rays.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "What is the approximate wavelength range of visible light?", "400 nm to 700 nm.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "What is the phase difference between the oscillating electric and magnetic fields in an EM wave?", "Zero (they are in the same phase).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Write the Ampere-Maxwell law equation and explain its physical significance.", "Integral of B.dl = mu_0 _ (I_c + eps_0 _ d(Phi_E)/dt). It shows that a changing electric field produces a magnetic field.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "How does a capacitor block DC but allow AC to pass through it? Explain using the concept of displacement current.", "In DC, flux becomes constant, so displacement current is zero. In AC, the continuously changing voltage changes the electric flux, generating a continuous displacement current across the plates.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Write the expression for the average energy density of an electromagnetic wave in a vacuum.", "u_avg = 1/2 _ eps_0 _ E_rms^2 + 1/2 _ (B_rms^2 / mu_0) = eps_0 _ E_rms^2.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Show that the momentum transferred by an EM wave of energy U completely absorbed by a surface is p = U/c.", "Since an EM wave carries energy, it also carries momentum. For complete absorption, momentum p = Energy / velocity = U / c.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "What is radiation pressure? Write its formula for a perfectly absorbing surface.", "The pressure exerted by an EM wave on a surface due to the transfer of momentum. Pressure P = Intensity / c.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "How are X-rays produced and what is one major practical application?", "Produced by bombarding a metal target with high-energy electrons. Used in medical diagnostics (detecting bone fractures).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Why are infrared waves often referred to as heat waves? What is their role in the greenhouse effect?", "Water molecules readily absorb IR waves, increasing their thermal motion (heat). They trap Earth's radiated heat, keeping the planet warm.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "A plane EM wave propagates in the z-direction. What can you say about the directions of its electric and magnetic field vectors?", "E and B vectors must lie in the xy-plane and must be mutually perpendicular.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "In an EM wave, the electric field oscillates at a frequency of 2 x 10^10 Hz and amplitude 48 V/m. What is the amplitude of the oscillating magnetic field?", "B0 = E0 / c = 48 / (3 x 10^8) = 1.6 x 10^-7 T.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Write the mathematical equations for the electric and magnetic fields of an EM wave propagating along the positive x-axis.", "E_y = E0 sin(kx - wt) and B_z = B0 sin(kx - wt).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Why is displacement current necessary for the logical consistency of Ampere's circuital law?", "Without it, Ampere's law gives different magnetic fields depending on the surface chosen near a charging capacitor, violating continuity.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Establish the relationship between conduction current and displacement current in a charging capacitor.", "They are exactly equal. I_d = eps_0 _ d(Phi_E)/dt = eps_0 _ d(EA)/dt = eps_0 _ A _ d(sigma/eps_0)/dt = A _ d(Q/A)/dt = dQ/dt = I_c.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Name the EM waves used for studying the crystal structure of solids and give the reason.", "X-rays, because their wavelength (around 1 Angstrom) is comparable to the interatomic spacing in crystals, allowing diffraction.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "How are radio waves produced?", "By the rapid acceleration and deceleration of electrons in conducting aerials (LC oscillating circuits).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "How are microwaves produced and why are they used in radar?", "Produced by special vacuum tubes (klystrons/magnetrons). Their short wavelength minimizes diffraction, allowing them to travel as a focused beam.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Identify the EM wave whose wavelength ranges from 1 mm to 700 nm and state its source.", "Infrared rays. Source: Hot bodies and molecules.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "An EM wave travels in a vacuum along the z-axis. E = E0 sin(kz - wt) i^. Find the direction of B.", "Since wave propagation (z) = E (x) cross B, B must be in the y-direction (j^).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "What happens to the intensity of an EM wave when it propagates in a vacuum?", "The total power remains constant, but intensity decreases as 1/r^2 from a point source due to spherical spreading.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Find the wavelength of an EM wave if its electric field is given by E = 50 sin(10^8 t - 0.5 x).", "Comparing with E = E0 sin(wt - kx), k = 0.5 rad/m. Wavelength lambda = 2*pi / k = 4*pi meters.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Electromagnetic Waves", "Write the expression for the intensity of an electromagnetic wave in terms of the maximum electric field E0.", "I = 1/2 _ c _ eps_0 \\* E0^2.", "HARD"),
    # Ray Optics and Optical Instruments
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "State the Mirror Formula.", "1/f = 1/v + 1/u", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "State the Lens Formula.", "1/f = 1/v - 1/u", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "What is Snell's Law of refraction?", "n1 sin(i) = n2 sin(r)", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "What is the relation between power of a lens and its focal length?", "P = 1/f (f in meters)", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "What is the SI unit of power of a lens?", "Diopter (D)", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "What are the two conditions for Total Internal Reflection (TIR)?", "Light travels from denser to rarer medium, and angle of incidence > critical angle", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Write the Lens Maker's Formula.", "1/f = (n - 1)(1/R1 - 1/R2)", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "What causes the phenomenon of a mirage?", "Total Internal Reflection due to atmospheric refraction", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Write the magnifying power formula for an astronomical telescope in normal adjustment.", "M = fo / fe", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Why is the objective lens of an astronomical telescope made with a large aperture?", "To increase its resolving power and light-gathering capability", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "State the laws of reflection.", "1. The incident ray, reflected ray, and normal lie in the same plane. 2. The angle of incidence equals the angle of reflection.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "State Snell's law of refraction.", "The ratio of the sine of the angle of incidence to the sine of the angle of refraction is a constant for a given pair of media (n1 sin i = n2 sin r).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "What is the critical angle?", "The angle of incidence in the denser medium for which the angle of refraction in the rarer medium is 90 degrees.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Write the formula for the power of a lens and state its SI unit.", "P = 1/f (f must be in meters). SI unit is Diopter (D).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Write the mirror formula and state the sign convention for focal length.", "1/f = 1/v + 1/u. f is negative for a concave mirror and positive for a convex mirror.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Define dispersion of light.", "The phenomenon of splitting of white light into its constituent colors when passing through a prism.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "What is the optical cause of a mirage?", "Total internal reflection of light due to atmospheric refraction in hot air layers near the ground.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "What is myopia and how is it corrected?", "Near-sightedness (inability to see distant objects clearly). Corrected using a concave (diverging) lens.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Write the formula for the magnifying power of a simple microscope when the image is formed at the near point (D).", "M = 1 + D/f", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "What is the condition for minimum deviation in a prism?", "The angle of incidence equals the angle of emergence (i = e), and the refracted ray inside the prism is parallel to its base.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Derive the Lens Maker's Formula.", "Consider refraction at two spherical surfaces. For surface 1: n2/v1 - n1/u = (n2-n1)/R1. For surface 2: n1/v - n2/v1 = (n1-n2)/R2. Adding them yields 1/f = (n21 - 1)(1/R1 - 1/R2).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Derive the formula for refraction at a single convex spherical surface separating two media of refractive indices n1 and n2.", "n2/v - n1/u = (n2 - n1)/R, derived using Snell's law for paraxial rays and exterior angle properties of triangles.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Explain the working principle of optical fibers.", "They work on the principle of total internal reflection. Light entering the core (higher refractive index) strikes the cladding boundary at an angle greater than the critical angle, undergoing repeated TIR.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Derive the expression for the equivalent focal length of two thin convex lenses in contact.", "For lens 1: 1/v1 - 1/u = 1/f1. For lens 2: 1/v - 1/v1 = 1/f2. Adding them gives 1/v - 1/u = 1/f1 + 1/f2. Hence, 1/F = 1/f1 + 1/f2.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Derive the magnifying power of a compound microscope.", "M = M_o * M_e = (v_o / u_o) * (1 + D / f_e). For image at infinity, M = (L / f_o) * (D / f_e).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Derive the magnifying power of an astronomical telescope in normal adjustment.", "M = beta / alpha = (h' / f_e) / (h' / f_o) = f_o / f_e.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Why is the objective lens of an astronomical telescope made with a very large aperture and large focal length?", "Large aperture gathers more light (increases brightness and resolving power). Large focal length increases magnifying power (M = f_o/f_e).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Derive the prism formula relating refractive index, angle of prism, and angle of minimum deviation.", "n = sin((A + delta_m) / 2) / sin(A / 2), obtained by applying Snell's law at minimum deviation where r1 = r2 = A/2 and i = (A + delta_m)/2.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "State Rayleigh's law of scattering. Use it to explain why the sky is blue.", "Intensity of scattered light is inversely proportional to the fourth power of wavelength (I prop 1/lambda^4). Blue light has a shorter wavelength and scatters much more than red.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Derive the expression for the lateral shift produced by a rectangular glass slab.", "x = t * sin(i - r) / cos(r), where t is the thickness of the slab.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Derive the relation between real depth and apparent depth for a liquid of refractive index n.", "Using paraxial approximation and Snell's law at a plane boundary, Apparent Depth = Real Depth / n.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "State three advantages of a reflecting telescope over a refracting telescope.", "1. No chromatic aberration. 2. Less spherical aberration (using parabolic mirrors). 3. Easier mechanical support (mirror is supported from the entire back).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Explain the formation of primary and secondary rainbows.", "Primary: One total internal reflection inside water drops (red on top). Secondary: Two total internal reflections (fainter, colors inverted, violet on top).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Draw a ray diagram and explain the working of a Cassegrain reflecting telescope.", "Light from a distant object hits a large concave primary mirror, reflects to a smaller convex secondary mirror, and is directed through a hole in the primary mirror to the eyepiece.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "A convex lens (n = 1.5) is immersed in a liquid of refractive index 1.65. How does its nature change?", "Since n_liquid > n_lens, the focal length becomes negative (1/f becomes negative in Lens Maker's formula). The convex lens starts acting as a diverging (concave) lens.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "If a convex lens of focal length f is cut into two equal halves horizontally, what is the focal length of each half?", "The focal length remains f, but the intensity of the image is halved because the aperture area is halved.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "If a convex lens of focal length f is cut into two equal halves vertically, what is the focal length of each half?", "The radius of curvature of one surface becomes infinity. Using Lens Maker's formula, the focal length of each half becomes 2f.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Derive the expression for the deviation produced by a thin prism.", "For small angles, sin(x) roughly equals x. Snell's law becomes i = n*r1 and e = n*r2. Deviation delta = i + e - A = n(r1 + r2) - A = nA - A = A(n - 1).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "A convex lens of f = 20 cm and a concave lens of f = -10 cm are placed in contact. Find the power of the combination.", "P = P1 + P2 = (100/20) + (100/-10) = 5D - 10D = -5 Diopters. The combination acts as a diverging lens.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Ray Optics and Optical Instruments", "Why does a diamond sparkle?", "Because of its very high refractive index (2.42) and correspondingly low critical angle (24.4 deg). Light entering it undergoes multiple total internal reflections before exiting.", "HARD"),
    # Wave Optics
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "What does Huygens' Principle state?", "Every point on a primary wavefront acts as a source of secondary wavelets", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "What is the shape of a wavefront originating from a point source?", "Spherical", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "Young's Double Slit Experiment demonstrates which phenomenon?", "Interference of light", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "What is the phase difference condition for constructive interference?", "Even multiple of π (ΔΦ = 2nπ)", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "What is the path difference condition for destructive interference?", "Odd multiple of λ/2 (Δx = (2n-1)λ/2)", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "Write the formula for fringe width in YDSE.", "β = λD / d", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "Define diffraction of light.", "The bending of light around the corners of an obstacle or aperture", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "What is the width of the central maximum in single-slit diffraction?", "2λD / a", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "State Brewster's Law for polarization.", "μ = tan(ip) (where ip is polarizing angle)", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "Does the fringe width change if the YDSE apparatus is immersed in water?", "Yes, it decreases because wavelength decreases in a denser medium", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "State Huygens' Principle.", "Every point on a given wavefront acts as a fresh source of secondary wavelets, which travel in all directions with the speed of light.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "What is the shape of a wavefront diverging from a point source?", "Spherical wavefront.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "What is the relationship between phase difference (Delta phi) and path difference (Delta x)?", "Delta phi = (2 * pi / lambda) * Delta x", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "State the condition for constructive interference in terms of path difference.", "Path difference must be an integral multiple of wavelength: Delta x = n * lambda (where n = 0, 1, 2...).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "State the condition for destructive interference in terms of path difference.", "Path difference must be an odd half-integral multiple of wavelength: Delta x = (2n - 1) * lambda / 2.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "Write the formula for fringe width in Young's Double Slit Experiment (YDSE).", "beta = (lambda * D) / d", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "Define diffraction of light.", "The phenomenon of bending of light around the corners of an obstacle or aperture whose size is comparable to the wavelength of light.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "Write the formula for the linear width of the central maximum in single-slit diffraction.", "Width = (2 * lambda * D) / a", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "What are coherent sources of light?", "Two sources are coherent if they emit light waves of the same frequency and maintain a constant phase difference.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "What is the ratio of maximum to minimum intensity in an interference pattern if the ratio of amplitudes is a/b?", "I_max / I_min = (a + b)^2 / (a - b)^2", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "Prove the laws of reflection of light on the basis of Huygens' wave theory.", "Draw incident and reflected wavefronts. Prove the congruence of the triangles formed by the wavefronts and the reflecting surface to show angle i = angle r.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "Prove Snell's law of refraction on the basis of Huygens' wave theory.", "Using geometry of incident and refracted wavefronts, sin(i) = (v1*t)/AC and sin(r) = (v2*t)/AC. Dividing them gives sin(i)/sin(r) = v1/v2 = n2/n1.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "Derive the expression for fringe width in Young's Double Slit Experiment.", "Path diff Delta x = S2P - S1P = y*d/D. For bright fringe, y*d/D = n*lambda -> y_n = n*lambda*D/d. Fringe width beta = y_(n+1) - y_n = lambda*D/d.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "What happens to the interference pattern in YDSE if the whole apparatus is immersed in water?", "The wavelength of light decreases in water (lambda' = lambda/n). Since fringe width beta is proportional to lambda, the fringe width decreases.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "What happens to the central bright fringe in YDSE if a thin glass slab of thickness t and refractive index n is placed in front of one slit?", "The entire fringe pattern shifts towards the side of the covered slit by a distance Shift = (D/d) * (n - 1) * t. The central fringe remains bright.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "State the essential conditions for obtaining sustained interference of light.", "1. Sources must be coherent. 2. Sources must be monochromatic. 3. Amplitudes should be nearly equal. 4. Slits must be narrow and close to each other.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "Derive the expression for the angular width of the central maximum in a single slit diffraction pattern.", "The first minimum occurs at sin(theta) = lambda/a. For small angles, theta = lambda/a. The central max spans from -theta to +theta, so angular width = 2*lambda/a.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "State three main differences between interference and diffraction patterns.", "1. Interference is superposition from two slits; diffraction is from different parts of the same slit. 2. All interference bright fringes have equal intensity; diffraction maxima intensities decrease rapidly. 3. Interference fringes are equally spaced; diffraction fringes are not.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "Why is the central maximum in a single slit diffraction pattern twice as wide as the secondary maxima?", "The central max extends from the first minimum on the left (-lambda/a) to the first minimum on the right (+lambda/a), making its total width 2*lambda/a. Secondary maxima lie between successive minima (e.g., 2lambda/a to 3lambda/a), giving a width of lambda/a.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "Draw the intensity distribution curve for single slit diffraction. Write the intensities of the first two secondary maxima relative to the central maximum I_0.", "Central max = I_0. First secondary max approx I_0 / 22. Second secondary max approx I_0 / 61.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "Two independent monochromatic light sources cannot produce a sustained interference pattern. Why?", "Because independent sources undergo random phase changes millions of times per second. Their phase difference is not constant, so the interference pattern shifts too rapidly for the eye to see, resulting in uniform illumination.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "What happens to the YDSE pattern if the monochromatic light source is replaced by a white light source?", "The central fringe remains white (zero path difference for all colors). A few colored fringes are seen on either side, and further away, overlapping colors produce uniform white illumination.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "How does the angular width of the central maximum in diffraction change if the slit width is increased?", "Angular width is 2*lambda/a. If the slit width (a) increases, the angular width of the central maximum decreases (the pattern becomes narrower and sharper).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "What is the effect on the interference fringes in YDSE if the distance between the two slits (d) is halved?", "Fringe width beta = (lambda * D) / d. If d is halved, the fringe width doubles.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "In YDSE, the slits are separated by 0.28 mm and the screen is placed 1.4 m away. If the distance between the central bright fringe and the fourth bright fringe is 1.2 cm, determine the wavelength of light used.", "y_4 = 4 * lambda * D / d. lambda = (1.2 x 10^-2 * 0.28 x 10^-3) / (4 * 1.4) = 600 nm.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "Two coherent sources produce interference. What is the phase difference between two points on the same wavefront?", "Zero. By definition, a wavefront is the locus of all points in the same phase of oscillation.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "If the slit width in a single slit diffraction experiment is made double the original width, how does this affect the size and intensity of the central diffraction band?", "The size (angular width) becomes half. The peak intensity becomes four times the original intensity.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "In YDSE, the intensities of the two slits are I and 4I. Find the maximum and minimum intensities in the interference pattern.", "Amplitudes are a and 2a. I_max = (a + 2a)^2 = 9a^2 = 9I. I_min = (2a - a)^2 = a^2 = I. Ratio is 9:1.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "Why can't longitudinal waves (like sound) be polarized?", "Polarization requires vibrations perpendicular to the direction of wave propagation. Longitudinal waves vibrate parallel to propagation, so they lack the necessary geometry for polarization.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Wave Optics", "A plane wavefront is incident on a convex lens. Sketch the shape of the emergent wavefront.", "The emergent wavefront converges towards the focal point, making it a converging spherical wavefront.", "HARD"),
    # Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Write the formula for the energy of a photon.", "E = hν (or E = hc/λ)", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Define work function.", "The minimum energy required to eject an electron from a metal surface", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "The photoelectric effect proves which nature of light?", "Particle nature", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "State Einstein's photoelectric equation.", "K_max = hν - Φ", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "What is a photon?", "A quantum or packet of light energy", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "What does stopping potential depend upon?", "The frequency of incident light and nature of the material", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Define threshold frequency.", "The minimum frequency of incident light below which no photoelectric emission occurs", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Write the de Broglie wavelength formula.", "λ = h/p (or λ = h/mv)", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "What is the momentum of a photon of wavelength λ?", "p = h/λ", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Write the formula for the de Broglie wavelength of an electron accelerated through potential V.", "λ = 1.227 / √V nm", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Define work function of a metal.", "The minimum amount of energy required by an electron to just escape from the metal surface.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Define threshold frequency.", "The minimum frequency of incident radiation below which photoelectric emission does not occur, regardless of intensity.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Define stopping potential (cut-off potential).", "The minimum negative (retarding) potential given to the anode at which the photoelectric current becomes zero.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Write the formula for the energy of a photon.", "E = h _ nu = (h _ c) / lambda", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Write the de Broglie wavelength formula.", "lambda = h / p = h / (m * v)", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "What is the photoelectric effect?", "The phenomenon of emission of electrons from a metal surface when light of suitable high frequency falls on it.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Convert 1 electron-volt (eV) into Joules.", "1 eV = 1.6 x 10^-19 Joules.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "How does the photoelectric current change with an increase in the intensity of incident light?", "It increases linearly, provided the frequency is above the threshold frequency.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "How does stopping potential change with an increase in the frequency of incident light?", "It becomes more negative linearly (its magnitude increases).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Write the formula for the momentum of a photon.", "p = E / c = h / lambda", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Write Einstein's photoelectric equation and explain its terms.", "K_max = h*nu - Phi_0. K_max is the maximum kinetic energy of emitted electrons, h*nu is incident photon energy, and Phi_0 is the work function.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "State three reasons why the wave theory of light fails to explain the photoelectric effect.", "1. It cannot explain the existence of a threshold frequency. 2. It predicts K_max should depend on intensity, not frequency. 3. It predicts a time delay for emission, but it is instantaneous.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "State the laws of photoelectric emission.", "1. Instantaneous process. 2. Current proportional to intensity. 3. Exists threshold frequency. 4. Max KE depends only on frequency, not intensity.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "In a graph of stopping potential (V_0) versus frequency (nu), what do the slope and the x-intercept represent?", "The slope represents h/e (Planck's constant over elementary charge). The x-intercept represents the threshold frequency (nu_0).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "In a graph of maximum kinetic energy (K_max) versus frequency (nu), what do the slope and y-intercept represent?", "The slope represents Planck's constant (h). The negative y-intercept represents the work function (Phi_0).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Derive the formula for the de Broglie wavelength of an electron accelerated through a potential V.", "Kinetic Energy K = eV. Momentum p = sqrt(2mK) = sqrt(2meV). de Broglie wavelength lambda = h / p = h / sqrt(2meV) = 1.227 / sqrt(V) nm.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Calculate the maximum kinetic energy of electrons emitted from a metal surface of work function 2.0 eV when illuminated by light of wavelength 400 nm.", "E = hc/lambda = 1240 eV nm / 400 nm = 3.1 eV. K_max = E - Phi_0 = 3.1 eV - 2.0 eV = 1.1 eV.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "An alpha particle and a proton are accelerated through the same potential difference V. Find the ratio of their de Broglie wavelengths.", "lambda = h / sqrt(2mqV). lambda_a / lambda_p = sqrt((m_p*q_p) / (m_a*q_a)) = sqrt((1*1) / (4*2)) = 1 / sqrt(8) = 1 / (2*sqrt(2)).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Calculate the de Broglie wavelength of a thermal neutron at temperature T.", "Kinetic energy of thermal neutron K = 3/2 _ k_B _ T. lambda = h / sqrt(2mK) = h / sqrt(3 _ m _ k_B * T).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "What is meant by the effective mass of a photon? Write its formula.", "Though a photon has zero rest mass, it possesses momentum and energy while moving. Using E=mc^2 and E=h*nu, effective mass m = (h*nu) / c^2 = h / (c*lambda).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Show that the de Broglie wavelength of a particle of rest mass m0 and kinetic energy K is lambda = h / sqrt(2*m0*K).", "Non-relativistically, p^2 / 2m0 = K, so p = sqrt(2*m0*K). Substituting into lambda = h/p gives the result.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "A monochromatic light source of power P and frequency nu emits photons. How many photons are emitted per second?", "Energy of one photon E = h*nu. Total energy per second = P. Number of photons per second N = P / E = P / (h*nu).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "What factor determines the work function of a metal?", "The nature of the metal (its atomic structure and how tightly its free electrons are bound) and its surface impurities.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Can X-rays cause the photoelectric effect? Justify.", "Yes. X-rays have a much higher frequency (and energy) than visible or UV light, well above the threshold frequency of all metals.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Why are alkali metals (like Na, K) highly photosensitive?", "Alkali metals have only one valence electron which is loosely bound to the nucleus, resulting in a very low work function, making them sensitive even to visible light.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "If the distance between a point light source and the photoelectric cell is doubled, what is the effect on stopping potential and photoelectric current?", "Stopping potential remains unchanged (it depends only on frequency). Photoelectric current becomes one-fourth (intensity I is proportional to 1/r^2).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "How is stopping potential related to the maximum kinetic energy of the emitted photoelectrons?", "K_max = e \\* V_0, where e is the charge of an electron and V_0 is the stopping potential.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Find the ratio of the de Broglie wavelengths of a proton and an alpha particle having the same kinetic energy.", "lambda = h / sqrt(2mK). Since K is same, lambda is proportional to 1/sqrt(m). lambda_p / lambda_a = sqrt(m_a / m_p) = sqrt(4/1) = 2:1.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Find the ratio of the de Broglie wavelengths of a proton and an alpha particle having the same momentum.", "lambda = h / p. Since momentum (p) is the same for both, their de Broglie wavelengths are identical. Ratio is 1:1.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Light of frequency 1.5 times the threshold frequency falls on a photosensitive material. What happens to the photoelectric current if the frequency is halved and intensity is doubled?", "Frequency becomes 0.75 times the threshold frequency. Since it is below the threshold, photoelectric emission stops completely, and the current becomes zero.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Dual Nature of Radiation and Matter", "Calculate the maximum kinetic energy of electrons emitted from a metal surface of work function 2.0 eV when illuminated by light of wavelength 400 nm.", "E = hc/lambda = 1240 eV nm / 400 nm = 3.1 eV. K_max = E - Phi_0 = 3.1 eV - 2.0 eV = 1.1 eV.", "HARD"),
    # Atoms
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "What did Rutherford's alpha-particle scattering experiment discover?", "The atomic nucleus", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "What is the approximate size of a nucleus?", "10^-15 m to 10^-14 m (1 to 10 fm)", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "State Bohr's quantization condition for angular momentum.", "mvr = nh / 2π", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "What is the energy of an electron in the ground state of a hydrogen atom?", "-13.6 eV", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "Write the formula for the energy of an electron in the nth orbit of hydrogen.", "E_n = -13.6 / n^2 eV", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "The Balmer series of the hydrogen spectrum lies in which electromagnetic region?", "Visible region", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "The Lyman series of the hydrogen spectrum lies in which electromagnetic region?", "Ultraviolet region", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "Write the Rydberg formula for spectral lines.", "1/λ = R (1/n1^2 - 1/n2^2)", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "What is the ionization energy of a hydrogen atom?", "13.6 eV", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "How does the radius of the nth Bohr orbit scale with principal quantum number n?", "It is directly proportional to n^2", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "What was the main conclusion of Rutherford's alpha scattering experiment?", "Most of the atom's mass and its entire positive charge are concentrated in a tiny central core called the nucleus.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "Define distance of closest approach.", "The minimum distance from the nucleus to which an energetic alpha particle can approach before its kinetic energy entirely converts to electrostatic potential energy and it turns back.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "Define impact parameter.", "The perpendicular distance of the initial velocity vector of the alpha particle from the central axis of the target nucleus.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "State Bohr's quantization condition for angular momentum.", "The orbital angular momentum of an electron is an integral multiple of h/(2*pi) (i.e., mvr = n*h/(2*pi)).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "Write the proportionality relation between the radius of the nth Bohr orbit and the principal quantum number n.", "Radius r is directly proportional to n^2 (r = n^2 * r0).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "Write the proportionality relation between the energy of an electron and the principal quantum number n.", "Energy E is inversely proportional to n^2 (E = -13.6 / n^2 eV).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "What is the energy of an electron in the ground state of a hydrogen atom?", "-13.6 eV.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "In which region of the electromagnetic spectrum does the Lyman series of hydrogen lie?", "Ultraviolet (UV) region.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "In which region of the electromagnetic spectrum does the Balmer series of hydrogen lie?", "Visible region.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "Write the Rydberg formula for the spectral lines of hydrogen.", "1/lambda = R * (1/n_f^2 - 1/n_i^2)", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "Derive the expression for the radius of the nth Bohr orbit of a hydrogen atom.", "Centripetal force = Electrostatic force: mv^2/r = (1/4*pi*eps_0)*(e^2/r^2). Using mvr = nh/2pi, substitute v to get r = (eps_0 _ h^2 _ n^2) / (pi _ m _ e^2).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "Derive the expression for the total energy of an electron in the nth Bohr orbit.", "KE = 1/2 mv^2 = e^2 / (8*pi*eps_0*r). PE = - e^2 / (4*pi*eps_0*r). Total Energy E = KE + PE = - e^2 / (8*pi*eps_0*r). Substituting r yields E = - (m*e^4) / (8*eps_0^2*h^2*n^2).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "Why is the total energy of an electron in an atom negative?", "The negative sign indicates that the electron is bound to the nucleus by attractive electrostatic forces. Energy must be supplied to free it.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "Calculate the longest wavelength of the Balmer series of the hydrogen spectrum.", "Longest wavelength means minimum energy transition (n_i = 3 to n_f = 2). 1/lambda = R(1/4 - 1/9) = 5R/36. lambda = 36 / 5R = 656.3 nm.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "Calculate the shortest wavelength of the Balmer series of the hydrogen spectrum.", "Shortest wavelength means maximum energy transition (n_i = infinity to n_f = 2). 1/lambda = R(1/4 - 0) = R/4. lambda = 4 / R = 364.6 nm.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "Explain the origin of spectral lines using Bohr's model.", "When an electron absorbs energy, it jumps to a higher orbit. It is unstable there and drops back to a lower orbit, emitting the energy difference as a photon of specific frequency (h*nu = E2 - E1).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "State three limitations of Bohr's atomic model.", "1. Applicable only to single-electron species (H, He+, Li2+). 2. Cannot explain fine structure of spectral lines. 3. Cannot explain Zeeman or Stark effects.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "Use de Broglie's hypothesis to prove Bohr's second postulate of quantization of angular momentum.", "For a stable orbit, the circumference must hold an integer number of wavelengths: 2*pi*r = n*lambda. Since lambda = h/(mv), 2*pi*r = n*h/(mv), so mvr = nh/(2*pi).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "Find the ratio of the radii of the first three Bohr orbits of a hydrogen atom.", "Since r is proportional to n^2, the ratio for n=1, 2, 3 is 1^2 : 2^2 : 3^2, which is 1 : 4 : 9.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "What is the energy required to excite an electron from the ground state to the first excited state in a hydrogen atom?", "Ground state E1 = -13.6 eV. First excited state (n=2) E2 = -13.6/4 = -3.4 eV. Energy required = E2 - E1 = -3.4 - (-13.6) = 10.2 eV.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "What is the ionization energy of a hydrogen atom?", "The energy required to move an electron from the ground state (n=1) to infinity. E = E_infinity - E_1 = 0 - (-13.6 eV) = 13.6 eV.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "In which regions of the EM spectrum do the Paschen, Brackett, and Pfund series lie?", "All three series lie in the Infrared (IR) region.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "What happens to the potential energy and kinetic energy of an electron when it is excited to a higher orbit?", "As r increases, potential energy increases (becomes less negative). Kinetic energy decreases (since velocity decreases as 1/n).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "What is the ratio of kinetic energy to potential energy of an electron in a Bohr orbit?", "KE = - Total Energy (E). PE = 2 * Total Energy (2E). Therefore, KE / PE = E / 2E = 1 / -2 = -1/2.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "How does the speed of an electron in a hydrogen atom vary with the principal quantum number n?", "Speed v is inversely proportional to n (v = v0 / n).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "How does the frequency of revolution of an electron in a Bohr orbit vary with n?", "Frequency f = v / (2*pi*r). Since v prop 1/n and r prop n^2, f is proportional to 1/n^3.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "Compare the radii of the first Bohr orbit of H, He+, and Li2+.", "Radius r is proportional to 1/Z. For H(Z=1), He+(Z=2), Li2+(Z=3), the ratio is 1 : 1/2 : 1/3.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "Determine the distance of closest approach of an alpha particle (charge 2e) of kinetic energy K towards a target nucleus of charge Ze.", "At closest approach, Initial KE = Electrostatic PE. K = 1/(4*pi*eps_0) _ (2e _ Ze) / r0. Therefore, r0 = (1/(4*pi*eps_0)) \\* (2Ze^2 / K).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "Why do a very small fraction of alpha particles scatter at large angles (> 90 deg) in Rutherford's experiment?", "Because the entire positive charge and mass are concentrated in an incredibly small nucleus, requiring a direct, head-on collision to cause strong Coulombic repulsion.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Atoms", "If the principal quantum number n increases, what happens to the energy gap between successive energy levels?", "The energy gap (Delta E) decreases rapidly as n increases. E_n is proportional to -1/n^2, so levels get closer together near the ionization limit.", "HARD"),
    # Nuclei
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "What are isotopes?", "Atoms of the same element with the same atomic number but different mass numbers", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "What are isobars?", "Atoms of different elements with the same mass number but different atomic numbers", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Write the empirical relation between nuclear radius R and mass number A.", "R = R0 * A^(1/3)", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "What is the approximate value of the constant R0 in the nuclear radius formula?", "1.2 fm (1.2 x 10^-15 m)", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "What is meant by mass defect?", "The difference between the sum of the masses of individual nucleons and the actual mass of the nucleus", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Write Einstein's mass-energy equivalence relation.", "E = mc^2", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "What does high binding energy per nucleon indicate?", "High stability of the nucleus", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Define nuclear fission.", "The splitting of a heavy nucleus into two or more lighter nuclei of comparable mass", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Define nuclear fusion.", "The combining of two or more lighter nuclei to form a single heavier nucleus", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Calculate the energy equivalent of 1 atomic mass unit (1 u) in MeV.", "Using E = mc^2, E = (1.6605 x 10^-27 kg) * (2.9979 x 10^8 m/s)^2 = 1.4924 x 10^-10 J. In MeV: E = 1.4924 x 10^-10 / (1.602 x 10^-13) = 931.5 MeV.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Define isotopes and give an example.", "Atoms of the same element having the same atomic number (Z) but different mass numbers (A). Example: 1H1, 1H2, 1H3.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Define isobars and isotones.", "Isobars: Same mass number (A), different atomic number (Z). Isotones: Same number of neutrons (A-Z), different atomic number.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Write the empirical relation between the radius of a nucleus and its mass number.", "R = R0 * A^(1/3), where R0 is a constant approx 1.2 fm.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "What can you say about the density of different nuclei?", "Nuclear density is constant and independent of the mass number A (approx 2.3 x 10^17 kg/m^3).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Define mass defect.", "The difference between the sum of the rest masses of individual nucleons (protons and neutrons) and the actual rest mass of the nucleus.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Define binding energy of a nucleus.", "The minimum energy required to completely separate a nucleus into its constituent protons and neutrons.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "What is the energy equivalent of 1 atomic mass unit (amu or u)?", "1 u = 931.5 MeV.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Define nuclear fission.", "The process in which a heavy nucleus breaks into two or more intermediate-mass fragments, accompanied by the release of a large amount of energy.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Define nuclear fusion.", "The process in which two light nuclei combine to form a single heavier nucleus, accompanied by the release of energy.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "State two properties of the strong nuclear force.", "1. It is the strongest force in nature but has a very short range (~2-3 fm). 2. It is independent of charge (p-p, n-n, p-n forces are roughly equal).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Draw the binding energy per nucleon (BE/A) vs mass number (A) curve and state its main features.", "Curve peaks at A=56 (Iron, ~8.8 MeV). It is nearly constant (8.0 MeV) for 30 < A < 170, and drops for A < 30 and A > 170, indicating lighter and heavier nuclei are less stable.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Explain how the BE/A curve justifies energy release in nuclear fission.", "Heavy nuclei (A > 170) have lower BE/A. When they split into medium-mass fragments (30 < A < 170), the BE/A of the products is higher, meaning they are more tightly bound, releasing the energy difference.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Explain how the BE/A curve justifies energy release in nuclear fusion.", "Very light nuclei (A < 10) have low BE/A. When they fuse to form a heavier nucleus, the BE/A of the product is higher, indicating increased stability and the release of enormous energy.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Why is nuclear fusion difficult to achieve in the laboratory?", "Fusion requires bringing positively charged nuclei extremely close against immense Coulomb repulsive forces, necessitating extremely high temperatures (~10^7 K) and pressures (thermonuclear conditions).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Calculate the binding energy of an alpha particle (4He). Mass of proton=1.0078u, neutron=1.0087u, He nucleus=4.0026u.", "Mass defect = (2 * 1.0078 + 2 * 1.0087) - 4.0026 = 0.0304 u. Binding Energy = 0.0304 * 931.5 = 28.3 MeV.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Draw a graph showing the variation of potential energy of a pair of nucleons as a function of their separation.", "A potential well graph. Repulsive (positive PE) for r < 0.8 fm. Highly attractive (negative minimum PE) at r approx 0.8 fm. Asymptotically drops to zero for r > 3 fm.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Find the ratio of the nuclear densities of two nuclei having mass numbers A1 and A2.", "Density = Mass / Volume. Mass prop to A. Volume = 4/3 pi R^3 prop to A. Density = A/A = constant. Ratio is 1:1 for all nuclei.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Explain the concept of a chain reaction in nuclear fission.", "When a U-235 nucleus fissions after absorbing a neutron, it releases 2-3 extra neutrons. These neutrons can trigger further fissions, creating a self-sustaining cascade.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "What is the role of a moderator in a nuclear reactor? Give examples.", "To slow down fast-moving neutrons produced in fission so they can efficiently cause further fission of U-235. Examples: Heavy water, graphite.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "What is the role of control rods in a nuclear reactor? Give an example.", "To absorb excess neutrons to control the rate of the chain reaction and prevent a meltdown. Example: Cadmium or Boron rods.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "What is meant by the Q-value of a nuclear reaction?", "The energy absorbed or released during a nuclear reaction, calculated by Q = (Mass of reactants - Mass of products) * c^2.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Why is the mass of a stable nucleus always less than the sum of the masses of its constituent nucleons?", "The difference in mass (mass defect) is converted into binding energy during the formation of the nucleus, which holds the nucleons together tightly.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Draw a plot of potential energy of a pair of nucleons as a function of their separation. Mark the regions where the nuclear force is attractive and repulsive.", "The PE is minimum at separation r_0 (~0.8 fm). For r < r_0, the force is strongly repulsive. For r > r_0, the force is attractive.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Two nuclei have mass numbers in the ratio 1:8. What is the ratio of their nuclear radii?", "R_1 / R_2 = (A_1 / A_2)^(1/3) = (1/8)^(1/3) = 1/2. The ratio is 1:2.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Complete the following nuclear fission reaction: 235_92_U + 1_0_n -> 144_56_Ba + ... + 3 1_0_n", "By conserving mass and atomic numbers: 236 = 144 + A + 3 -> A = 89. 92 = 56 + Z + 0 -> Z = 36. The missing product is Krypton (89_36_Kr).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "What is the difference between a controlled and uncontrolled chain reaction?", "Controlled: On average, exactly one neutron from each fission causes another fission (nuclear reactors). Uncontrolled: Multiple neutrons cause exponentially increasing fissions (atomic bomb).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "What is the source of stellar energy (like in our Sun)?", "Thermonuclear fusion. Primarily the proton-proton cycle where four hydrogen nuclei (protons) fuse to form one helium nucleus, releasing vast energy.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Find the ratio of radii of nuclei 13Al27 and 52Te125.", "R1/R2 = (A1/A2)^(1/3) = (27/125)^(1/3) = 3/5.", "HARD"),
    # Semiconductor Electronics
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "What is the typical energy band gap in insulators?", "Greater than 3 eV", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Who are the majority charge carriers in an n-type semiconductor?", "Electrons", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Who are the majority charge carriers in a p-type semiconductor?", "Holes", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "What kind of dopant is added to an intrinsic semiconductor to make it n-type?", "Pentavalent impurity (e.g., Phosphorus, Arsenic)", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "What kind of dopant is added to an intrinsic semiconductor to make it p-type?", "Trivalent impurity (e.g., Boron, Aluminum)", "EASY"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "What does the depletion region of a p-n junction contain?", "Immobile positive and negative ions (no free charge carriers)", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "How does forward biasing affect the width of the depletion region?", "It decreases the width of the depletion region", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "How does reverse biasing affect the width of the depletion region?", "It increases the width of the depletion region", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Two nuclei have mass numbers in the ratio 1:8. What is the ratio of their nuclear radii?", "R_1 / R_2 = (A_1 / A_2)^(1/3) = (1/8)^(1/3) = 1/2. The ratio is 1:2.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "What is the maximum theoretical efficiency of a full-wave rectifier?", "81.2%", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Define energy band gap.", "The energy gap between the top of the valence band and the bottom of the conduction band where no electron energy levels can exist.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Distinguish between intrinsic and extrinsic semiconductors.", "Intrinsic are pure semiconductors (n_e = n_h). Extrinsic are doped with impurities to increase conductivity (n_e != n_h).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "What dopant is used to make an n-type semiconductor and what are its majority carriers?", "Pentavalent impurities (e.g., Phosphorus, Arsenic, Antimony). Majority carriers are electrons.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "What dopant is used to make a p-type semiconductor and what are its majority carriers?", "Trivalent impurities (e.g., Boron, Aluminum, Indium). Majority carriers are holes.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "What is the depletion region in a p-n junction?", "A narrow region on either side of the junction completely devoid of mobile charge carriers, containing only immobile ions.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "What is potential barrier in a p-n junction?", "The potential difference developed across the depletion region which prevents the further majority carrier diffusion across the junction.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "How is a p-n junction forward biased?", "The p-side is connected to the positive terminal and the n-side to the negative terminal of the battery.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "How is a p-n junction reverse biased?", "The p-side is connected to the negative terminal and the n-side to the positive terminal of the battery.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "What is a rectifier?", "An electronic device (typically using diodes) that converts alternating current (AC) into direct current (DC).", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "What is the basic function of a photodiode?", "It converts light energy into electrical energy, operating in reverse bias to detect optical signals or light intensity.", "MODERATE"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Explain the formation of the depletion region and potential barrier in a p-n junction.", "Due to concentration gradients, electrons diffuse from n to p and holes from p to n, leaving behind immobile positive and negative ions near the junction. This creates an electric field that eventually stops further diffusion.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Draw and explain the V-I characteristics of a p-n junction diode.", "In forward bias, current rises exponentially after overcoming the knee voltage (~0.7V for Si). In reverse bias, a small, constant leakage current flows until the breakdown voltage, where current increases sharply.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Explain the working of a half-wave rectifier using a circuit diagram and input/output waveforms.", "Uses one diode. During the positive half cycle of AC, the diode is forward biased and conducts. During the negative half cycle, it is reverse biased and blocks current. Output is pulsating DC.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Explain the working of a center-tap full-wave rectifier.", "Uses a center-tapped transformer and two diodes. D1 conducts during the positive half cycle and D2 conducts during the negative half cycle. Both direct current through the load resistor in the same direction, rectifying the full wave.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "What is the role of a capacitor filter in a rectifier circuit?", "The capacitor charges to the peak voltage during conduction and discharges slowly through the load when the diode is off, smoothing out the pulsating DC into a much steadier DC voltage.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Explain the working principle of a solar cell.", "Light incident on the p-n junction creates electron-hole pairs. The built-in electric field of the depletion region sweeps electrons to the n-side and holes to the p-side, generating an open-circuit photovoltage.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Draw the V-I characteristics of a solar cell. Why does it lie in the fourth quadrant?", "The curve intercepts the V-axis (open circuit voltage) and I-axis (short circuit current) in the 4th quadrant because a solar cell draws no current from the external circuit; rather, it supplies current to it.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Explain the working of a Light Emitting Diode (LED).", "A heavily doped p-n junction in forward bias. Injected electrons and holes recombine at the junction, releasing energy in the form of photons. The energy (color) depends on the band gap of the semiconductor.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Give three advantages of LEDs over conventional incandescent bulbs.", "1. Low operational voltage and less power consumption. 2. Fast action (no warm-up time). 3. Very long life and ruggedness.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Draw energy band diagrams to differentiate between conductors, insulators, and semiconductors.", "Conductors: Overlapping valence and conduction bands. Insulators: Large band gap (>3 eV). Semiconductors: Small band gap (<3 eV), allowing thermal excitation of electrons.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Draw the energy band diagram of an n-type semiconductor showing the donor energy level.", "The donor energy level lies just below the bottom of the conduction band, making it very easy for donor electrons to transition into the conduction band at room temperature.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Draw the energy band diagram of a p-type semiconductor showing the acceptor energy level.", "The acceptor energy level lies just above the top of the valence band, allowing electrons from the valence band to easily transition up, leaving behind holes.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Why is the depletion region wider in reverse bias and narrower in forward bias?", "In reverse bias, the external field aids the built-in field, pulling majority carriers further away from the junction. In forward bias, the external field opposes the built-in field, pushing carriers into the junction.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Define dynamic resistance of a diode.", "It is the ratio of a small change in voltage to the corresponding small change in current in the non-linear region of the V-I curve (r_d = Delta V / Delta I).", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Why is a photodiode operated in reverse bias?", "In reverse bias, the dark current (due to minority carriers) is very small. When light falls on it, the fractional change in this minority current is highly measurable and directly proportional to light intensity.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Why is GaAs (Gallium Arsenide) preferred for making solar cells despite Si being cheaper?", "GaAs has an ideal band gap (~1.53 eV) matching the solar spectrum peak, and a much higher optical absorption coefficient, requiring a much thinner layer of material to absorb the sunlight.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Semiconductor Electronics", "Calculate the maximum wavelength of light that can be detected by a photodiode made of a semiconductor with a band gap of 2.8 eV.", "E = hc/lambda. lambda = hc/E = (6.63x10^-34 * 3x10^8) / (2.8 * 1.6x10^-19) = 444 nm.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Why is the mass of a stable nucleus always less than the sum of the masses of its constituent nucleons?", "The difference in mass (mass defect) is converted into binding energy during the formation of the nucleus, which holds the nucleons together tightly.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Draw a plot of potential energy of a pair of nucleons as a function of their separation. Mark the regions where the nuclear force is attractive and repulsive.", "The PE is minimum at separation r_0 (~0.8 fm). For r < r_0, the force is strongly repulsive. For r > r_0, the force is attractive.", "HARD"),
    ("Physics", "Nuclei", "Complete the following nuclear fission reaction: 235_92_U + 1_0_n -> 144_56_Ba + ... + 3 1_0_n", "By conserving mass and atomic numbers: 236 = 144 + A + 3 -> A = 89. 92 = 56 + Z + 0 -> Z = 36. The missing product is Krypton (89_36_Kr).", "HARD"),
    # Solutions
    ("Chemistry", "Solutions", "Define molarity.", "Number of moles of solute dissolved in one litre of solution", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Solutions", "Define molality.", "Number of moles of solute dissolved in one kilogram of solvent", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Solutions", "State Henry's Law.", "The partial pressure of a gas in vapor phase is proportional to its mole fraction in solution", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Solutions", "What is an ideal solution?", "A solution that obeys Raoult's law over the entire range of concentration", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Solutions", "Name the four colligative properties.", "Relative lowering of vapor pressure, elevation of boiling point, depression of freezing point, osmotic pressure", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Solutions", "What are isotonic solutions?", "Two solutions having the same osmotic pressure at a given temperature", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Solutions", "What is the van't Hoff factor (i)?", "The ratio of normal molar mass to anomalous molar mass (or observed colligative property to calculated)", "HARD"),
    ("Chemistry", "Solutions", "What type of deviation from Raoult's law is shown by an ethanol-acetone mixture?", "Positive deviation", "HARD"),
    ("Chemistry", "Solutions", "What happens to the freezing point of water when a non-volatile solute is added?", "It is depressed or decreases", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Solutions", "Define ebullioscopic constant (Kb).", "Elevation in boiling point when the molality of the solution is unity", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Solutions", "Why do aquatic species feel more comfortable in cold water than in warm water?", "The solubility of oxygen is higher at lower temperatures", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Solutions", "What is reverse osmosis?", "Applying pressure greater than the osmotic pressure to reverse the direction of solvent flow", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Solutions", "State Raoult's law for a solution containing a non-volatile solute.", "The relative lowering of vapor pressure is equal to the mole fraction of the solute", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Solutions", "Give an example of a maximum boiling azeotrope.", "A mixture of Nitric acid (68%) and water (32%)", "HARD"),
    # Electrochemistry
    ("Chemistry", "Electrochemistry", "What is the unit of molar conductivity?", "S cm^2 mol^-1", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Electrochemistry", "What is the standard electrode potential of the Standard Hydrogen Electrode (SHE)?", "Zero volts", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Electrochemistry", "Define cell constant.", "The ratio of distance between electrodes to their area of cross section (l/A)", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Electrochemistry", "State Kohlrausch's law of independent migration of ions.", "Limiting molar conductivity of an electrolyte is the sum of individual contributions of the anion and cation", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Electrochemistry", "What is a primary battery?", "A battery that cannot be recharged and reused once the reaction is complete", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Electrochemistry", "State Faraday's first law of electrolysis.", "The mass of substance deposited at any electrode is directly proportional to the quantity of electricity passed", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Electrochemistry", "Write the Nernst equation for a general electrode reaction.", "E = E0 - (RT/nF) * ln([Product]/[Reactant])", "HARD"),
    ("Chemistry", "Electrochemistry", "Which metals are used in a fuel cell?", "Porous carbon electrodes containing catalysts like finely divided platinum or palladium", "HARD"),
    ("Chemistry", "Electrochemistry", "What is the relation between standard cell potential and standard Gibbs free energy change?", "ΔG° = -nFE°cell", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Electrochemistry", "Why does the conductivity of a solution decrease with dilution?", "Because the number of ions per unit volume decreases", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Electrochemistry", "Why does molar conductivity increase with dilution?", "Due to an increase in ionic mobility and degree of dissociation", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Electrochemistry", "What is the function of a salt bridge?", "It completes the electrical circuit and maintains electrical neutrality in the two half-cells", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Electrochemistry", "Name the electrolyte used in a dry cell (Leclanché cell).", "A moist paste of NH4Cl and ZnCl2", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Electrochemistry", "Can you store copper sulphate solution in a zinc pot?", "No, because zinc is more reactive and will displace copper from the solution", "EASY"),
    # Chemical Kinetics
    ("Chemistry", "Chemical Kinetics", "Define rate of a reaction.", "The change in concentration of a reactant or product per unit time", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Chemical Kinetics", "What is the unit of rate constant for a zero-order reaction?", "mol L^-1 s^-1", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Chemical Kinetics", "What is the unit of rate constant for a first-order reaction?", "s^-1", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Chemical Kinetics", "Define half-life of a reaction.", "The time in which the concentration of a reactant is reduced to one half of its initial concentration", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Chemical Kinetics", "What is molecularity of a reaction?", "The number of reacting species taking part in an elementary reaction, which must collide simultaneously", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Chemical Kinetics", "Write the Arrhenius equation.", "k = A * e^(-Ea/RT)", "HARD"),
    ("Chemistry", "Chemical Kinetics", "What is activation energy?", "The minimum extra amount of energy required by reacting molecules to get converted into products", "HARD"),
    ("Chemistry", "Chemical Kinetics", "How does a catalyst increase the rate of a reaction?", "By providing an alternate pathway with lower activation energy", "HARD"),
    ("Chemistry", "Chemical Kinetics", "What is a pseudo first-order reaction?", "A reaction that is truly of a higher order but under certain conditions behaves as a first-order reaction", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Chemical Kinetics", "What is the relationship between t99% and t90% for a first-order reaction?", "t99% = 2 * t90%", "HARD"),
    ("Chemistry", "Chemical Kinetics", "How does the rate constant generally vary with a 10-degree rise in temperature?", "It becomes nearly double", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Chemical Kinetics", "Identify the order of a reaction with rate constant k = 2.5 x 10^-4 L mol^-1 s^-1.", "Second order", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Chemical Kinetics", "Define threshold energy.", "The minimum energy that reacting molecules must possess to undergo effective collisions", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Chemical Kinetics", "Give an example of a zero-order reaction.", "Decomposition of ammonia gas on a hot platinum surface", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Chemical Kinetics", "If the plot of ln[R] vs time gives a straight line, what is the order of the reaction?", "First order", "EASY"),
    # d and f Block Elements
    ("Chemistry", "d and f Block Elements", "Why are d-block elements called transition elements?", "Because their properties are transitional between s and p block elements", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "d and f Block Elements", "What is the general electronic configuration of transition elements?", "(n-1)d^(1-10) ns^(1-2)", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "d and f Block Elements", "Why are Zn, Cd, and Hg not considered transition elements?", "Because they have completely filled d-orbitals in their ground state as well as in their common oxidation states", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "d and f Block Elements", "What is lanthanoid contraction?", "The steady decrease in atomic and ionic radii of lanthanoids with increasing atomic number", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "d and f Block Elements", "What is the most common oxidation state of lanthanoids?", "+3", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "d and f Block Elements", "Why do transition metals form complex compounds?", "Due to their small ionic size, high ionic charge, and availability of vacant d-orbitals", "HARD"),
    ("Chemistry", "d and f Block Elements", "Why are transition metal ions generally colored?", "Due to d-d transitions of electrons", "HARD"),
    ("Chemistry", "d and f Block Elements", "Why do transition metals act as good catalysts?", "Due to their ability to adopt multiple oxidation states and form complexes", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "d and f Block Elements", "Why is Cu+ ion not stable in aqueous solution?", "It undergoes disproportionation to form Cu2+ and Cu", "HARD"),
    ("Chemistry", "d and f Block Elements", "What is actinoid contraction?", "The gradual decrease in size of actinoids across the series, which is greater than lanthanoid contraction", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "d and f Block Elements", "Which transition metal of the 3d series exhibits the maximum number of oxidation states?", "Manganese (Mn)", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "d and f Block Elements", "Calculate the spin-only magnetic moment of a divalent ion (Z=25) in aqueous solution.", "5.92 BM", "HARD"),
    ("Chemistry", "d and f Block Elements", "Why is the E° value for the Mn3+/Mn2+ couple highly positive?", "Because Mn2+ has a highly stable half-filled d5 configuration", "HARD"),
    ("Chemistry", "d and f Block Elements", "What is Mischmetal?", "An alloy consisting mainly of lanthanoid metals used in making magnesium-based alloys", "MODERATE"),
    # Coordination Compounds
    ("Chemistry", "Coordination Compounds", "Define a ligand.", "An atom, ion, or molecule that donates a pair of electrons to the central metal atom/ion", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Coordination Compounds", "What is the coordination number of a central metal atom?", "The total number of ligand donor atoms to which the metal is directly bonded", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Coordination Compounds", "What is an ambidentate ligand?", "A unidentate ligand that can ligate through two different atoms (e.g., NO2-, SCN-)", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Coordination Compounds", "What is the denticity of EDTA?", "Hexadentate (it has six donor atoms)", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Coordination Compounds", "What is the primary valence in Werner's theory?", "The oxidation state of the central metal atom, which is ionizable", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Coordination Compounds", "Explain the term 'spectrochemical series'.", "The arrangement of ligands in order of their increasing crystal field splitting energy (field strength)", "HARD"),
    ("Chemistry", "Coordination Compounds", "What geometry is formed by a complex with coordination number 6?", "Octahedral", "HARD"),
    ("Chemistry", "Coordination Compounds", "What type of isomerism is shown by [Co(NH3)5(SO4)]Br and [Co(NH3)5Br]SO4?", "Ionization isomerism", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Coordination Compounds", "Write the IUPAC name of K3[Fe(CN)6].", "Potassium hexacyanoferrate(III)", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Coordination Compounds", "What is a chelate ligand?", "A bi- or polydentate ligand that forms a ring structure with the central metal ion", "EASY"),
    ("Chemistry", "Coordination Compounds", "Using VBT, predict the shape of [Ni(CN)4]2-.", "Square planar", "HARD"),
    ("Chemistry", "Coordination Compounds", "Is [CoF6]3- an inner or outer orbital complex?", "Outer orbital complex", "HARD"),
    ("Chemistry", "Coordination Compounds", "What is the coordination number of Pt in [Pt(en)2Cl2]2+?", "Six", "MODERATE"),
    ("Chemistry", "Coordination Compounds", "Define Crystal Field Splitting Energy (CFSE).", "The energy difference between the t2g and eg sets of d-orbitals", "MODERATE"),
    # Haloalkanes and Haloarenes
